    "summary": "Janine Brogt works as dramaturg, writer and translator for theatre, opera and dance. She got an MA in Theatre and English Literature from Amsterdam University (UvA). She has worked as  dramaturg and artistic consultant for Toneelgroep Amsterdam, Kampnagel Internationale Kulturfabrik (Hamburg) and Zuidelijk Toneel Globe. In dramaturgy she has longstanding work-relationships with directors Ivo van Hove, Pierre Audi, Gerardjan Rijnders, and choreographer Ted Brandsen (Dutch National Ballet). She is a lecturer  at Utrecht University and Hogeschool for the Arts in Amsterdam, where she is also the artstic consultant for the Directors' School. \n\nShe translated over thirty plays by English, American and German dramatists, notably: Shakespeare, Goethe, Pinter, O\u2019Neill, Bernhard and Kleist. As an adaptator she is known for taking on complex projects: Faust I and II, Oresteia, Strindbergs To Damascus,  Orhan Pamuks The House of Silence and H\u00f6lderlins Der Tod des Empedokles.\n\nHer love of musictheatre has led her to write libretti for a number of opera\u2019s by different composers,  Mannetje Jas (composer Boudewijn Tarenskeen), Waiting for Miss Monroe (composer Robin de Raaff)  For Pierre Audi she wrote  texts  to be incorporated in performances of works by Karel Goeyvaerts and Alban Berg. Her balletlibretti include new versions of Firebird and Coppelia for The Dutch National Ballet.\n\nDramaturgy for opera include Ivo van Hove\u2019s productions of Vec Makropulos (Dutch National Opera), Iolantha (DNO), Wagner\u2019s Ring cycle (De Vlaamse Opera), Idomeneo (La Monnaie),Schreker\u2019s Der Schatzgr\u00e4ber (DNO), Verdi\u2019s Macbeth in Lyon, Mazeppa in Berlin (Komische Oper) and La Clemenza di Tito in Brussels.\n\nRecent work in theatre dramaturgy includes  Richard 3 at Orkater (Shakespeare / Tom Waits & Kathleen Brennan), Tsjechov 3 (Seagull, Vanya and Cherry Orchard)  at Hummelinck Stuurman and  adaptations of Orhan Pamuk's The House of Silence and Philippe Claudel's Il y a long temps que je t'aime.",
